  "text": "Postnatal day (P) 7-13 mice (CD-l) were killed by decapitation, in accordance with institutional guidelines. Cerebella were quickly removed from the skull and placed in cold (5°C) Hanks' balanced salt solution (40 mM glucose, 2.5 mM Hepes) that was oxygenated with 95% 0,. 5% CO, to a final DH of 7.4. Prior to cutting. cerebella were embedded in 20% gelatin and sectioned sag&tally into 300-400 pm thick slices on a Vibro Slice microtome (Stoelting Co.). After sectioning, pia mater and gelatin were carefully removed under a dissecting microscope. Only slices obtained from the middle region of the cerebellum were used for this study. To label migrating granule cells, cerebellar slices were incubated for 30 min at 37°C in a fluorescent lipophilic carbocyanine dye [ 1,l '-dioctadecyl-3,3,3',3'-tetramethylindocarbocyanine perchlorate (Dir)] (10 ).&ml) (Molecular Probes) added to the cell culture medium [CITATION_1] . The incubation medium consisted of minimum essential medium (Gibco) supplemented with 40 mM glucose, 1.8 mM glutamine, 24 mM NaHCO,, penicillin (90 U/ml), and streptomycin (90 &ml). After rinsing with the incubation medium, brain slices were maintained in an incubator (37°C 95% air, 5% CO,) for an additional 24 hr. Brain slices were then transferred into the chamber of a microincubator (PDMI-2, Medical System Corp.) attached to the stage of an inverted microscope (IMT-2, Olympus Corp.). Chamber temperature was kept at 37.0 ? 0.5\"C using a temperature controller Medical System Corp.) , and the slices were provided with constant gas flow (95% O,, 5% CO,). To prevent movement of the slice preparation during observation, a nylon net glued to a small silver wire ring was placed over the preparations.",
